### What are Server Components?

React Server Components (RSC) are components that run **exclusively on the server**. They never send JavaScript to the client, reducing bundle size and improving performance.

### Benefits

- **Zero Client JavaScript**: Server components don't add to the client bundle
- **Direct Backend Access**: Query databases, read files, access APIs directly
- **Automatic Code Splitting**: Only client components are bundled for the browser
- **Improved SEO**: HTML is fully rendered on the server
- **Security**: Sensitive logic stays server-side

### Async Server Components

Server components can be async functions:

```jsx
// app/posts/page.js
export default async function Posts() {
  const posts = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts').then(r => r.json());

  return (
    <ul>
      {posts.map(post => (
        <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### Direct Database Access

No need for API routes — connect directly:

```jsx
import db from '@/lib/db';

export default async function Users() {
  const users = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users');

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### Server-Only Code

Use the `server-only` package to prevent client bundling:

```bash
npm install server-only
```

```jsx
import 'server-only';

// This code will error if imported by a client component
export const apiKey = process.env.SECRET_API_KEY;
export async function getData() {
  // sensitive logic
}
```

### What Server Components Cannot Do

- Cannot use hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useContext`)
- Cannot use browser APIs
- Cannot handle user interactions (onClick, onChange)
- Cannot use event listeners

For interactivity, extract a Client Component.

### Default in App Router

All components in the App Router are **Server Components by default**. To make a Client Component, add `'use client'` at the top of the file.

codeExample:
// app/page.js — Server Component (default)
import 'server-only';

export default async function Home() {
  const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
    cache: 'no-store',
  }).then(r => r.json());

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Server Rendered</h1>
      <ul>
        {data.items.map(item => (
          <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
